One percent of the world's population suffers from schizophrenia, making it a prominent psychopathology. Hallucinations, delusions, disorganized thought patterns, and erratic conduct are only some of the symptoms. a) Symptoms Schizophrenia symptoms may be broken down into two groups: positive and negative. Hallucinations, delusions, and mental disorders including slurred speech and jumbled ideas are all examples of positive symptoms. Low motivation, emotion numbness, and trouble interacting with others are all negative signs. b) Pharmaceuticals and neurotransmitters/hormones: Antipsychotic drugs, which work by affecting certain neurotransmitters in the brain, are the mainstay of therapy for schizophrenia. Many antipsychotic medications aim to block the D2 dopamine receptor. The overactivity of dopamine is considered to contribute to schizophrenia, hence these medications suppress its production. In addition to dopamine receptors, a different family of antipsychotics known as atypical antipsychotics also targets serotonin receptors. Schizophrenia has a high heritability, with estimates ranging from 70 to 80 percent. Schizophrenia has been linked to changes in multiple genes, including those involved in brain formation and immunological function, as well as dopamine and glutamate neurotransmission. The prefrontal cortex, hippocampus, and thalamus of people with schizophrenia have been shown to operate abnormally in neuroimaging studies. Reduced gray matter in the prefrontal cortex and the hippocampus, for example, have both been linked to schizophrenia in research. Researchers believe that aberrant dopamine activity in the striatum and mesolimbic system is a primary mechanism driving the positive symptoms of schizophrenia in those who suffer from it. Schizophrenia, in its whole, is a multifaceted condition that affects many neuronal circuits and chemical messengers in the brain and manifests in a wide variety of symptoms. Antipsychotic drugs are the mainstay of treatment, and there is a significant hereditary component. Neuroimaging and other studies have uncovered many brain abnormalities and processes that may contribute to the etiology and manifestations of the condition. 